Project Overview

Designed and implemented a private subnet inside an existing Amazon VPC to host resources that should not be directly accessible from the internet. The project focused on network isolation, subnet-specific routing, and subnet-level traffic filtering using custom Route Tables and Network ACLs.


Business Scenario

A company hosts a public-facing web application but needs to protect backend resources such as databases and internal application servers.

Instead of exposing every resource to the internet, production AWS environments isolate sensitive workloads inside private subnets where they can only communicate with trusted resources.

This project demonstrates that architecture.


Architecture Decisions

Instead of using the VPC's default networking configuration, I created dedicated networking components for the private subnet.


Dedicated Route Table

The private subnet received its own Route Table without a default route (0.0.0.0/0) pointing to an Internet Gateway.

This ensures resources inside the subnet cannot receive direct inbound internet traffic.


Dedicated Network ACL

Instead of relying on the default Network ACL, I associated the subnet with a custom ACL to provide explicit subnet-level traffic control.

Although the initial rules deny all traffic, this follows a security-first approach where only required communication is later permitted.

Validation

Verified that

Private subnet successfully created
Route Table correctly associated
